<article>
    <h1>IM&#xAD;AGES OF THE LIT&#xAD;TLE RED DOT</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201204/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-04"><time>2020-12-04</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE</span>
        - <span role="byline">Ong Sor Fern Se&#xAD;nior Cul&#xAD;ture Cor&#xAD;re&#xAD;spon&#xAD;dent sor&#xAD;fern@sph.com.sg</span>
    </section>

    <p>MAR­GINS: DRAW­ING PIC­TURES OF HOME</p>
    <p>Spend a leisurely and re­ward­ing af­ter­noon look­ing at Sin­ga­pore through the lenses of 15 pho­tog­ra­phers at this thought­fully cu­rated show. From silly and whim­si­cal to nos­tal­gic and gritty, the pho­tog­ra­phers each have a dis­tinc­tive point of view which, when jux­ta­posed against each other, present thought-pro­vok­ing im­ages of this lit­tle red dot.</p>
    <p>My favourites in­clude Zakaria Zainal’s por­trait series Our Gurkhas, which cap­ture the men who served qui­etly and long in Sin­ga­pore, and Wil­fred Lim’s State Of Soli­tary, shot dur­ing the cir­cuit breaker and fea­tur­ing hi­lar­i­ously ob­ses­sive-compulsive as­sem­blies of ob­jects such as two fat lime but­ter­fly cater­pil­lars on a pas­sion fruit peel.</p>
    <p>An­other stand­out is Ang Song Nian’s Hang­ing Heavy On My Eyes (left), in which he used the Pol­lu­tant Stan­dards In­dex to de­ter­mine ex­po­sure time for his prints. The re­sult is a vis­ual rep­re­sen­ta­tion of Sin­ga­pore’s pol­lu­tion lev­els in 2016, cap­tured in 366 shades of grey, one for each day of the year.</p>
    <p>WHERE ArtS­cience Mu­seum, 6 Bayfront Av­enue</p>
    <p>MRT Bayfront</p>
    <p>WHEN Till Feb 28, 11am to 7pm daily</p>
    <p>AD­MIS­SION $6 for Sin­ga­pore res­i­dents</p>
    <p>INFO str.sg/JEGc</p>

